Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** — it spins up your app in-memory with no real network listener, and gives you an `HttpClient` you can wire into the MCP C# SDK's transport.

### Setup

```csharp
// NuGet packages:
//   Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
//   ModelContextProtocol  (official C# SDK)

public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _factory = factory;
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ListTools_ReturnsExpectedTools()
    {
        // The factory's in-memory HttpClient — no real port opened
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Connect using the SDK's Streamable-HTTP transport
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                // Any other options (e.g. custom headers)
            },
            httpClient          // ← inject the in-memory client
        );

        await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var tools = await mcpClient.ListToolsAsync();

        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
        Assert.Contains(tools, t => t.Name == "my-tool");
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsCorrectResult()
    {
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
            },
            httpClient
        );

        await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var result = await mcpClient.CallToolAsync(
            "my-tool",
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" });

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
        Assert.Contains("expected output", result.Content[0].Text);
    }
}
```

### Key ideas

| Concept | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No real server** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts your app in-process; `CreateClient()` returns an `HttpClient` backed by an in-memory `TestServer`. |
| **Full protocol fidelity** | The MCP SDK's transport speaks real SSE / Streamable-HTTP against your middleware — same code path as production. |
| **Custom config** | Override `WebApplicationFactory.ConfigureWebHost` to swap DI services (e.g. mock databases) for isolated tests. |
| **`Program` visibility** | Add `<InternalsVisibleTo Include="YourTestProject" />` in the server's `.csproj`, or declare a partial `Program` class, so the test project can reference the entry point. |

This gives you end-to-end MCP coverage (initialize → list → call → shutdown) entirely in-process.
